				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${F}_{{PhO}}^{K}=\frac{{Q}_{{real}}}{{Q}_{{PhO}}}\le 1$$\end{document}

Volta limited his study to the evaluation of processes’ material efficiency and energy consumption. Keichel extended the methods to include instantaneous values as well. Values describing current operating conditions provide information on processes’ current efficiency, thus enabling the identification of inefficient process states and intervention in real time. Moreover, specific processes can be targeted for optimization. The power-based PhO factor is defined by power in real terms and power under physically optimal conditions. It can also be specified by deriving the energy-based PhO factor over time (Keichel 2017):
